        "content": {
            "text": "3.2.1 Focus Groups and Individual Interviews.  We conducted six focus groups with two to four participants in each, and two indi-vidual interviews due to participant no-shows in two additionally planned focus groups. All sessions were conducted remotely via Zoom videoconferencing and lasted 90 minutes. Each session was facilitated by two researchers. Focus groups were an appropriate method for our research question as they have been shown to be great at \"facilitating the grounding of the research in participants’ own understandings of the issue(s) under question [94]\". In particu-lar, focus groups have been commonly used for participatory action research, as they \"enable the development of collective understand-ings of shared problems—and (often) solutions to the problems\" [94]. We structured our focus groups and interviews to investigate the impact of the platform on worker well-being, with a focus on workers’ work preferences and perceived fairness of the platform. The focus groups and interviews began with the introduction of the study’s focus on worker well-being and a quick overview of phys-ical, psychological, and fnancial well-being. Then, we presented fve sets of two diferent ride requests, the main \"gig\" or work of drivers, in order to present concrete contexts to ground discussion (we provide the ride requests that we used in our supplementary materials). The ride requests had two types of information that were revealed to participants in two phases: information the Uber driver app currently shows to drivers at the time of request such as the time to pick up and rider’s rating, and hypothetical information that Uber could provide such as rider cancellation rate or feedback"
        },
